               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179409170235"></xptr>565. 
               
                  <persName id="t17940917-107-defend1347" type="defendantName">
                     STEPHEN 
                     LANGLEY
                  <interp inst="t17940917-107-defend1347" type="surname" value="LANGLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-defend1347" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-defend1347" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-defend1347" type="age" value="35"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted, for <rs id="t17940917-107-off552" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-off552" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-off552" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               feloniously stealing, on the <rs id="t17940917-107-cd553" type="crimeDate">20th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-107-off552 t17940917-107-cd553"></join>, six pounds weight of iron nails, value 2s. two ounces weight of Singlo tea, value 6d.
            </rs> the goods of the 
               <persName id="t17940917-107-victim1348" type="victimName">
                     <rs id="t17940917-107-viclabel554" type="occupation">East India Company</rs>
                     <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-107-victim1348 t17940917-107-viclabel554"></join>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-victim1348" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-107-off552 t17940917-107-victim1348"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>MINNIKIN sworn.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know any thing of this transaction? - Yes, thoroughly. I am a labourer in the East India Company's warehouses, in <placeName id="t17940917-107-crimeloc555">Fenchurch-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17940917-107-crimeloc555" type="placeName" value="Fenchurch-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17940917-107-crimeloc555" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-107-off552 t17940917-107-crimeloc555"></join>; between the hours of eleven and twelve on Saturday last, I was coming down stairs, and on the first floor, along side of a nail box, I saw the prisoner. He is a bricklayer's labourer, employed by the Company; he was along side of the nail box; he was lifting the nails from the box, and putting them in his pocket; he observed that I see him put some in his pocket, and he dropped some on the stairs, and said that he wanted them, to put them in his shoes. I said nothing to him, but I went and told my fellow labourers that Longley had got some of the Company's property; and my fellow labourer went to the counting house to this gentleman, Mr. Duree. I went back to my employment, because I was requested to be back as soon as possible.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-107-person1349">
                  JOHN
                   DUREE
               <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1349" type="surname" value="DUREE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1349" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1349" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I belong to the East India Company. I am what they call an elder there. On Saturday last, about twelve o'clock, I believe it was, I was informed by the last witness, and another man, that the prisoner Langley had been taking some nails from a box on a stair case, belonging to the Company. Afterwards he went on the top of the house to work; I went to the top of the house after him, and called him down. I asked him what he had in his pocket? he said, nothing. I told him I was sure he had some nails of the Company. He then emptied the nails into an apron, belonging to one of the men, out of his pockets. I asked him if had got any more in his pocket, he said, he had not. I put my hand into his waistcoat pocket, and found there was some tea, two ounces and a quarter weight of Singlo tea. I sent for a Custom house officer that is here, and he took it from him; and he has got it in his possession. I asked him where he got the tea? he said, he thought there was no harm in it; and he went up, and pointed out the chest where he took it out from.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you make him any promise? - I did not.</p>
               <p>Q. Did any body else? - Not to my knowledge; I was there all the time.</p>
               <p>Q. What was the value of the nails? - Very likely three shillings. I gave them into the custody or one of our men.</p>
               <p>- HETCHELL sworn.</p>
               <p> I have got the nails; the prisoner took them out of his own pocket and delivered them into my possession; likewise I see the officer take the tea out of his pocket.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-107-person1350">
                  Q. 
               <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1350" type="given" value="Q."></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1350" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            What may be the value of the tea? - Eight shillings and six pence.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-107-person1351">
                  Q. 
               <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1351" type="given" value="Q."></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-person1351" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            What sort of nails are they? - What they call small congou nails.</p>
               <p>Q. How many nails are there? - Six or seven pounds.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I had a piece of tiling off, and the bricklayer was not in the way to lath it on, and I went down and took some nails on purpose to lay it on as soon as possible I could; the lath nails don't run very little larger than them; I did it to get it lathed in as soon as possible I could, because of the rain; and when I went down to get some lath nails there was some tea laying down along side of the chest, and I scratched it up and took some of it, and they asked me what chest it came out of? and I shewed them.</p>
               <p>The prisoner called three witnesses, who gave him a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17940917-107-verdict556" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-verdict556" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. (Aged 35.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17940917-107-punish557" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-107-punish557" type="punishmentCategory" value="corporal"></interp>
